The paper focuses on adapting AutoAugment, a data augmentation algorithm, to natural language processing tasks, specifically dialogue generation. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.CL (Computation and Language) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves training a controller to discover effective augmentation policies, which involves machine learning techniques, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) another likely sub-category. The paper also explores conditioning the controller on the source inputs of the target task, which involves some level of artificial intelligence, making cs.AI another possible sub-category. The paper also involves searching over the space of various combinations of atomic operations, which involves optimization techniques, making cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions AutoAugment's focus on computer vision tasks, suggesting that cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) may also be a possible sub-category.
